    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "The historic Academy Building, a brick schoolhouse built in 1838, now houses the East Bloomfield Historical Society.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        3
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 2"
      ],
      "source": "https://www.visitfingerlakes.com/plan-your-trip/ontario-county-ny/bloomfield-and-west-bloomfield/"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "East Bloomfield Station grew into the town’s business hub after a railroad opened in 1854, bringing mills, hotels, and a bank to the area.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        16,
        17
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://villageofbloomfieldny.gov/history"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "The Village of Bloomfield embraces its past with a self‑guided walking tour that highlights well‑preserved homes, churches, and the John and Mary Dickson House.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        4,
        11,
        12
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 2"
      ],
      "source": "https://www.visitfingerlakes.com/plan-your-trip/ontario-county-ny/bloomfield-and-west-bloomfield/"
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "text": "The Vintage Tracks Museum showcases early 20th‑century farm equipment, including classic crawler tractors that once powered local agriculture.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        18
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 2"
      ],
      "source": "https://www.visitfingerlakes.com/plan-your-trip/ontario-county-ny/bloomfield-and-west-bloomfield/"
    },
    {
      "id": 6,
      "text": "Bloomfield’s name honors the Seneca villages that once occupied the area, with sites now known as Fort Hill, Factory Hollow, and Bloomfield Station.",
